Russia debates its future
JAROSLAWL: Many say that Russia lacks a "civil society."
But it partly compensates with a rather interesting public space where serious topics are debated and fleeting glimpses of the powerful are not entirely confined to television snippets.
During the first two weeks of September, there were consecutive meetings of two important Russian political groups, the Valdai Discussion Club and the Global Policy Forum.
The former took place on a ship and ended with a dinner with Prime Minister Vladimir Putin in Sochi at the Black Sea.
Letzteres, in Jaroslawl, kulminierte in einem Symposium mit Präsident Dmitri Medwedew.
Wissenschaftler, Mitglieder von Denkfabriken und Journalisten (sowohl russische wie ausländische) diskutierten gemeinsam mit wichtigen Politikern und Unternehmensführern über Russlands Zukunft.
Drei Dinge machten diese Veranstaltungen auf typisch russische Weise zu etwas Besonderem.
Das Erste war das intensive Medieninteresse.
Sogar ein äußerst kamerascheuer Wissenschaftler konnte sich plötzlich als russischer Fernsehstar wiederfinden.
The Second was the willingness of both Putin and Medvedev to publicly engage with experts on their intellectual turf.
The only other recent Western political leader I can think of who had the confidence to do this was Bill Clinton.
Finally, the two events marked the emergence of competing political forums, each exuding the faint but unmistakable scent of mounting conflict.
To those with eyes to see, these two conferences provided a fascinating glimpse into a crumbling diarchy.
The main theme of the Valdai Conference was whether Russia's history and geography condemned it to authoritarian rule.
<s>Falls der Demokratie die Zukunft gehört, sei es dann Russlands Schicksal, das zu verpassen?
<s>Die Pessimisten – vor allem russische Historiker – machten geltend, dass es für Russland schwer wenn nicht gar unmöglich sei, sein autokratisches Erbe zu überwinden.
<s>Lew Beloussow von der Staatlichen Lomonosow-Universität in Moskau argumentierte, die Autokratie steige in Russland – gestützt durch die Passivität und die Leidensfähigkeit der Russen – immer wieder wie ein Phönix aus der Asche empor.
<s>Die Bolschewiken hätten die Autokratie von den Zaren geerbt; Putin habe das alte monarchische Prinzip der Salbung seines Nachfolgers wiederentdeckt und so den demokratischen Wettstreit um die Präsidentschaft umgangen.
<s>Radikale wie Wladimir Ryschkow erteilten diesem historischen Determinismus eine Absage. Man sollte, so Ryschkow, den Autoritarismus nicht durch Verweis auf die Geschichte legitimieren.
The protests were growing.
This was Putin's yoke, not history's, that weighed heavily upon Russia.
Much of this discussion lacked clarity, as such discussions tend to.
Most participants failed to distinguish between history as a constraint and history as a determinant.
Countries and civilizations can never fully overcome their history, but every history offers many different possibilities.
<s>Länder are not genetically programmed like animals.
The discussion about autocracy was inevitably linked to other topics.
Autocracy in Russia has been defended as necessary for a world empire.
But this leads to another question: Does Russia need a world empire?
Can Russia break with its imperial past and maintain normal relations with its recently independent neighbors such as Ukraine and Georgia?
<s>Can it actually be a completely "normal" actor on the world stage?
<s>At the meeting in Jaroslawl with Medvedev, the focus shifted to the connection between democracy and modernization.
<s>All agreed that Russia needs to diversify its economy and overcome its dependence on energy.
<s>As Medvedev emphasized, an economy based on raw materials is always vulnerable to fluctuations in raw material prices.
<s>But there are roughly two views on the relationship between political and economic modernization.
Putin's view is that democracy arises from a modern economy, as a kind of reward for hard work.
If the state drives modernization from the top down, then democracy will grow naturally, albeit slowly, as a result of increasing prosperity and a growing middle class.
The Kremlin's chief ideologist, Vladislav Surkov, has suggested that a genuine democracy requires a "democracy in the mind," implying that this desirable mental state is still far away in Russia.
The alternative view, put forward by people like Igor Yurgens, the head of Medvedev's preferred think tank, the Institute of Contemporary Development, is that democracy is a prerequisite for economic modernization.
They argue that the Russian state, in its current form, lacks any real incentive to reform its own bad economic habits—or those of the Russians.
<s>The current development confirms this.
<s>Russia has shown a modest recovery from the recession.
<s>Yet there is almost no innovation; the elites content themselves with leading comfortable lives with profits from the energy business, and corruption continues unchecked.
<s>Putin is the strong leader of a weak state, which, lacking a mobilizing element or feedback process, is unable to carry out a modernization project.
<s>There is a clear divide between Putin and Medvedev.
Medvedev is anything but Putin's puppet.
Both believe that democracy must come eventually, but while Putin emphasizes "later," Medvedev has added a liberating voice to the public discourse in Russia.
Cynics claim that this is merely a misleading routine following the pattern of "Good Cop, Bad Cop."
But words count, and a new rhetoric is a political force in its own right.
Medvedev's primary strategic goal now must be to secure a second term as president.
<s>He cannot openly challenge Putin's legacy, but must position himself as someone who goes beyond Putin.
<s>It is a delicate balancing act, because Putin could reclaim the presidency at any time if he believes that his former protege wants to dismantle the authoritarian state that Putin created.
<s>Nineteen years after the fall of communism, Russia's direction remains as unclear as ever.
<s>This is particularly important for the Russians, yet because Russia spans the enormous Eurasian landmass, the lack of clarity regarding Russia's future forces us all to be constantly concerned.
<s>Is Russia part of the West?
<s>Does its history and geography grant Russia an irreplaceably Eurasian perspective capable of mediating potential clashes between Western and Eastern civilizations or between Christianity and Islam?
<s>Russia cannot be neatly categorized geopolitically, but it remains too important to be ignored.
